==English==
===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, unknown origin, possibly Welsh ''[[moedrodd]]'' to worry or bother. [[Category:Unknown etymology]]. Possible alternatve from the Welsh '"meidda"' - to beg for whey or perhaps "meiddio" - to dare or venture. Bear in mind that the dd in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither.

====Pronunciation====
*{{IPA|/ˈmaɪθər/}}

====Intransitive verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}
# {{North England dialect}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]].

